03935nam a22006015i 9780823291885DE-B159720220329044247.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||220329t20222005nyu    fo  d z      eng d  a97808232918857 a10.1515/97808232918852doi  a(DE-B1597)566089  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anyucUS-NY 7aREL0420002bisacsh1 aDesmond, William, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aIs There a Sabbath for Thought? :bBetween Religion and Philosophy /cWilliam Desmond. 1aNew York, NY : bFordham University Press, c[2022] 4c©2005  a1 online resource (380 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aPerspectives in Continental Philosophy00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tPreface and Acknowledgments -- tBy Way of Introduction: The Intimate Universal—Between Religion and Philosophy -- t1 The Sleep of Finitude: On the Unease of Philosophy and Religion -- t2 Between Finitude and Infinity: Hegelian Reason and the Pascalian Heart -- t3 Religion and the Poverty of Philosophy -- t4 Religious Imagination and the Counterfeit Doubles of God -- t5 God Beyond the Whole: Between Solov’ev and Shestov -- t6 Caesar with the Soul of Christ: Nietzsche’s Highest Impossibility -- t7 The Secret Sources of Strengthening: On Courage -- t8 On the Betrayals of Reverence -- t9 Enemies: On Hatred -- t10 Is There a Sabbath for Thought? On Peace—Between Philosophy and Religion -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aSeeking to renew an ancient companionship between the philosophical and the religious, this book’s meditative chapters dwell on certain elemental experiences or happenings that keep the soul alive to the enigma of the divine. William Desmond engages the philosophical work of Pascal, Kant, Hegel, Nietzsche, Shestov, and Soloviev, among others, and pursues with a philosophical mindfulness what is most intimate in us, yet most universal: sleep, poverty, imagination, courage and witness, reverence, hatred and love, peace and war. Being religious has to do with that intimate universal, beyond arbitrary subjectivism and reductionist objectivism. In this book, he attempts to look at religion with a fresh and open mind, asking how philosophy might itself stand up to some of the questions posed to it by religion, not just how religion might stand up to the questions posed to it by philosophy. Desmond tries to pursue a new and different policy, one faithful to the light of this dialogue.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Mrz 2022) 7aRELIGION / Meditations.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertFordham University Press eBook-Package Backlist 2000-2013z978311070729840uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780823291885423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780823291885/original  a978-3-11-070729-8  Fordham University Press eBook-Package Backlist 2000-2013c2000d2013  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_PLTLJSIS  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_PLTLJSIS  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK